{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627566"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17128"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17128"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.3,0.01,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77243"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9818"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62750"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1003"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5003"},{"type":"tags","id":"5004"},{"type":"tags","id":"5005"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23016"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77243"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELow molecular weight heparins are anticoagulant medications used for prevention and treatment of venous thromboembolism with a different mechanism of action to that of heparin. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of low molecular weight heparin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activates antithrombin III to inhibit primarily factor Xa","Directly inhibits factor Xa without antithrombin III","Primarily inhibits factor IXa","Requires vitamin K as a cofactor","Directly activates fibrinolysis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELow molecular weight heparin primarily \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivates antithrombin III to inhibit primarily factor Xa \u003C/strong\u003E. It does so by irreversibly inhibiting factor Xa and, to a lesser degree, also inhibits factor IIa. In comparison, unfractionated heparin binds reversibly to both IIa and Xa with greater potency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly inhibits factor Xa without antithrombin III\u003C/strong\u003E:  antithrombin III is required as a cofactor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimarily inhibits factor IXa\u003C/strong\u003E: there are no significant effects on factor IXa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires vitamin K as a cofactor\u003C/strong\u003E: the mechanism is independent of vitamin K\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly activates fibrinolysis\u003C/strong\u003E: the fibrinolytic system is not affected. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low molecular weight heparin acts primarily by binding to and activating antithrombin III, which then irreversibly inhibits factor Xa and to a lesser degree factor IIa.","Low molecular weight heparin has less effect on thrombin (factor IIa) compared to unfractionated heparin.","Unfractionated heparin reversibly inhibits factor IIa and Xa in an antithrombin III-dependent manner"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62750"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17128"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62750"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T14:52:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T14:52:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9818"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77243"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedi